<dl id="n12143c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12143c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12143c"> 143(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bit of bread on a / pikestaff</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">le g&eacute;ographe romain Solinus, au III<sup>e</sup> si&egrave;cle de l&apos;&egrave;re chr&eacute;tienne, racontait que les m&egrave;res irlandaises pr&eacute;sentaient &agrave; leurs fils, sur la point d&apos;un glaive, la premi&egrave;re nourriture qu&apos;ils pouvaient prendre. <br><font color="green">[One trait common both to the Celts of the continent and those of the islands was their love of war. In the third century of the Christian era the Roman geographer, Solinus, tells us that <mark>Irish mothers used to present the first food their sons could take, on the point of a sword</mark>.]</font> <small> Riguet, Abb&eacute; <a name="RTSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RTSP"><cite title="source">Saint Patrice</cite></a> (1911) 4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12147d" href="c12all.htm#c12147d">VI.C.12:147(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
